  "body": "<!-- Please use this template while reporting a bug and provide as much info as possible. Not doing so may result in your bug not being addressed in a timely manner. Thanks!-->\r\n\r\n\r\n**What happened**:\r\n\r\nIf run kube-apiserver with `--bind-address={ip}` and not set `--advertise-address` , apiserver will use default route interface ip as kubernetes endpoint, this can be wrong when `bind-address`  is not on default route interface.\r\n\r\n> --advertise-address ip\r\nThe IP address on which to advertise the apiserver to members of the cluster. This address must be reachable by the rest of the cluster. If blank, the --bind-address will be used. If --bind-address is unspecified, the host's default interface will be used.\r\n\r\nFrom here we know this's not by design. But `EndpointReconciler` get apiserver public ip from `advertise-address`,  so if you have multi net interface and not run apiserver on default route interface, kubernetes endpoint will be wrong, and components access apiserver via `kubernetes.default` service will fail.\r\n\r\n\r\n**What you expected to happen**:\r\n\r\nkubernetes endpoint got the right apiserver ip\r\n\r\n**How to reproduce it (as minimally and precisely as possible)**:\r\n\r\n1. setup vm with 2 net interface, interface A is the default route.\r\n2. run k8s on interface B (just bind address on this, not set advertise-address)\r\n3. run `kubectl get ep kubernetes` will get wrong ip\r\n\r\n**Anything else we need to know?**:\r\n\r\n**Environment**:\r\n- Kubernetes version (use `kubectl version`): 1.13.1\r\n- Cloud provider or hardware configuration: vm\r\n- OS (e.g. from /etc/os-release): ubuntu 16.04\r\n- Kernel (e.g. `uname -a`):\r\n- Install tools: kubeadm\r\n- Others:\r\n\r\n<!-- DO NOT EDIT BELOW THIS LINE -->\r\n/kind bug\r\n\r\n/assign",
